When a person reaches a point in there life where they can no longer begin to understand all that has gone on, something must change.  The last several months have been torturous to me.  Not a day has gone by when i havent felt sick, and not a day has gone by when I haven't thought about my life.  

Let me be the first to say that I am not proud of my life, and the actions that belong to it.  To explain them would take more time than I have here or that of which i am willing to dedicate to this entry.  

For all of the lies which I have told.  I am sorry.  If you read this, and you know who you are, know that I have always wanted to tell you.  That everyday I saw you made it that much harder to not do so.  Know that I am so sorry, and that if you never want to speak to me again, I accept it, and that I hope you do well.  You are my best friend, and these couple of days have been unbearable---and i completely deserve this.  Do not think for a moment that I have not learned from all of this--I have-but that does not make her hurt dissapear-and I don't think there is anything short of killing myself that ever would.  I know longer know what to do--and I haven't for quite a long time.  But I know that I want to do good-just what that entails I am not sure.  I knew that I could not lie to you anylonger--but I had no idea on how to talk to you.  Hear me, I am truly sorry from the bottom of my heart for the way in whcih i told you-how was I to face you-a person who had trusted and been such a good friend?  I found it impossible.  I am a coward, and for the first time in a long time-I acted agaisnt that by talking to you. 

I don't know what else to say.  I am here.

Well, Matts still here in Bmore---and after running pointless errands around for the greater part of the day, there are several things which I came to realize.  One, banks are a pain in the ass.  For something as simple as getting a checking account number on a piece of official letter head, you have to wait in line, sit around, talk to an associate, then wait in line again, only to be helped.  Second, Geico is not the only way one can save on their car insurance.  Somehow, my car insurance has dipped by about $500 a year!  Finally, if you're told not to be late to work an hour before your shift starts, nyou should not be late.  I did it, got yelled at, and had to mop the floor.  Twice.  

But, work was a breeze.  It went by...somewhat slowly ( I never said it was a fast breeze) because tonight was not busy.  At all.  Anywho, around 7ish Pat and Matt came in, and got some dessert (which gave me the rare opportunity to sit down at work).  That was cool.  The last several hours ended without a high note, at which point I came home, driving the longest possible route because I really wanted to listen to some Josh Turner.  Good Stuff.

I walked in the door to find out that Pat finally has learned how to use the CD burner...if only Matt could also show me how to do that.  I took a very quick shower, and decided to go for a drive.

Matt needs a cord for his phone.  So naturally, he talked me into driving to the local walmart.  We got there, and guess what. Closed.  So, we decided to get on the highway and go find another walmart, because as everybody knows, if you look hard enough, or just if you look, one can always find a walmart.  We got there, in Glenburnie, it was closed.  So, since it was a nice night, we decided to take the long way back.  We went the back way on Route 1, and went through Brooklyn, and then Patapsco.  Somehow, we got lost in Patapso.  After being lost there, around 12:30 AM, we managed to find the belt way, and we started heading to DC.  

Shit, I had a half tank of gas, and I figured what the hell, I havent just taken a ride for a ride's sake in a very long time.  So it was Matt and me against the open road.  Half way to DC, we decided, heck, we know the capital to well, and we took the second upcoming exit.  We wound up in Laurel.  Neither one of us had been there before, so we decided to check things out.  After driving down Main Street (very original!) we saw the sign Open for a book store!  After driving past it several times, we decided to go take a look.  We parked, and while walking towards the book store, I thought just how great it would be to grab a burger.  Too late for anything like that I thought.  Well hell no. Across the street, was a classic 1950s burger joint.  We had to go, and we did.  It was cool, we got to talk to some random dude, who go figure, was from Frederick. We heard about his life story pretty much, and got some mini burgers for about seven bucks.  Not too shabby.

Well, back to the story.  We then left, and started walking to this bookstore.  I really couldn't wait to pick up some sort of used book, I mean come on what type of bookstore is open at 1 AM.  Well, we soon found out.  We opened the door, walked in, and quickly walked right back out.  It was a Porn/Book store. No no no.  We left quickly, got back in my car, and decided we'd had enough of Laurel.

We left Laurel, and got on the highway.  The highway felt good to be good on again.  Too good.  I realized I was going about 85 mph and that I passed a state trooper.  Realizing he got off the shoulder, and was prob going to give me a ticket, I quickly took the first exit off, and then the first exit off the smaller road.  
No ticket, but at the same time, a ticket to being lost.  and where did we wind up?  On Coca Cola Drive.  Has anybody ever heard of that?  Well it was okay, we were thirsty.  But after driving around we soon found out that the road did not have any vending machines.

Pity.

We got back on the belt way, and after passing and flipping off Scaggsville (which may or may not have pissed off the driver behind us) we headed back home.  

And now, our cool stoy has ended.

Gnight.

Well after several long days of being away from LJ-alas I have returned at the turn of the tide!  THe last couple of days have been full of things either directly or indirectly related to moving.  Finally, after many long hours and two days worth of labor the apartment is full!  Disorganized, but full.  First of all, many thanks to those who came out and helped.  SPecial thanks go to Geoff-(we could not have carried that killer sofa without you!)  

Additionally, in the last couple of days I have come to realize some things, and I feel that it is my duty to share them with you, my audience.  First of all, moving is a bitch.  Things seem to never want to work, and if there is a way things can go wrong, they do  aka Murphy's law.  But as hard as things may be, there is always something that will still surprise in a positive manner.  Look as most of you know, last year for me was quite rough, one from which I am still recovering.  AS painful of a year as it may have been, each day I feel just a little bit stronger, and a little bit more sure of myself.  Thank you all from the bottom of my heart.  Without my family, and without you, my friends, I could not be where I am today.  Matt, you have truly become a great friend, and I don't think that I can or will ever be able to say thanks.  (So...Thanks)  

Now, I stand on the edge, ready to move on, but still hurt from the past.  Yesterday I came across some photos that made me go lie down and cry.  I am still not over her.

I want to move on---though I am not ready.  I want to try and experience new things, but my heart aches nostaglicly (did I spell tht correctly?)  I guess my ranting has and must come to an end-so I will leave you with this thought:

The person who waits for things to come his or her way misses out on the fullness of life. 

The person who misses out on what life has to offer, is the one who waits when he should act.
